Antibody Responder Prediction Using Deep Learning Models¶

This notebook aims to benchmark longitudinal prediction models for immune response using time-series gene expression data derived from human viral vaccination studies. We implement and evaluate several deep learning models:

  • Logistic regression with PCA-reduced features and timepoint as predictor
  • SimpleRNN
  • GRU
  • LSTM
  • Transformer

These models are tested across three different batch correction methods:

  • Quantile Normalization (QN)
  • Regression-based residuals
  • ComBat

All models are assessed using stratified 5-fold cross-validation, and evaluated with:

  • Accuracy
  • F1-score
  • AUC (Area Under the ROC Curve)

Section 1: Data Loading and Preprocessing¶

We begin by loading the preprocessed gene expression matrices and associated sample metadata. Key preprocessing steps include:

  • By customized criteria load data from HR-VILAGE-3K3M Repo
  • Log2 transformation of RNA-seq samples
  • Quantile normalization across samples
  • Filtering genes with low mean and variance (bottom 25%)
  • Aligning metadata (combined_ID, timepoint_numeric, and responder2) to expression data

This ensures consistency across all input formats for both deep learning and traditional baseline models.

Sample Inclusion Criteria: We curated the dataset to include only influenza or influenza/pneumococcal vaccine studies with recorded antibody responses. Samples were limited to those collected before day 28 post-vaccination to capture early immune responses. Subjects receiving placebo or control vaccines (e.g., Saline, Pneumovax) were excluded. We binarized the antibody response into High-responder vs. Low-responder (combining Moderate and Non-responders) and removed studies with severely unbalanced class distributions. A unique combined_ID was generated for each subject to enable longitudinal modeling.

Section 2: Batch Effect Correction¶

To address technical variability across studies, we applied three normalization strategies. First, RNA-seq samples were log-transformed using log2(x + 1), and genes with low mean and variance (bottom 25%) were removed. Then, we applied Quantile Normalization (QN), which aligns the distribution of gene expression values across samples by assigning the average value at each rank, ensuring all samples share the same empirical distribution. Next, we applied ComBat, an empirical Bayes method that adjusts for known batch effects (study ID), and regression-based adjustment, where study-specific effects were regressed out using scanpy’s regress_out function. These approaches yielded three harmonized datasets (QN, ComBat, Regression) for downstream modeling and comparison.

In [5]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import scanpy as sc

# Copy expression and metadata
df = filtered_gene_expr_df.copy()
meta = filtered_meta.copy()

# Apply log2(x + 1) transform to RNA-seq samples
rna_seq_samples = meta[meta["platform"].str.lower() == "rna-seq"].index
df.loc[rna_seq_samples] = np.log2(df.loc[rna_seq_samples] + 1)

# Remove low mean and low variance genes
gene_means = df.mean(axis=0)
gene_vars = df.var(axis=0)

# Determine 25th percentile thresholds
mean_thresh = gene_means.quantile(0.25)
var_thresh = gene_vars.quantile(0.25)

# Filter: keep genes above both thresholds
genes_to_keep = gene_means[(gene_means > mean_thresh) & (gene_vars > var_thresh)].index
df = df[genes_to_keep]

#  R-style quantile normalization (transpose aware)
def quantile_normalize_matrix_rows_are_samples(expr_df):

    df_t = expr_df.T  # Now genes are rows, samples are columns

    # Sort each column (i.e., each sample)
    sorted_mat = np.sort(df_t.values, axis=0)

    # Compute mean of sorted values (average across samples for each rank)
    mean_ranks = np.mean(sorted_mat, axis=1)

    # Get rank indices for each gene in each sample
    ranks = df_t.rank(method="min", axis=0).astype(int) - 1

    # Replace values in original order based on rank
    norm_df_t = df_t.copy()
    for col in df_t.columns:
        norm_df_t[col] = [mean_ranks[r] for r in ranks[col].values]

    return norm_df_t.T  # Return to (samples x genes) shape

# Apply quantile normalization
qn_expr_df = quantile_normalize_matrix_rows_are_samples(df)

print(f"\n✅ Quantile-normalized expression shape: {qn_expr_df.shape}")

adata = sc.AnnData(df)

# Add batch information
adata.obs["batch"] = filtered_meta.loc[adata.obs_names, "study_ID"]

# Apply ComBat
sc.pp.combat(adata, key="batch")

combat_expr_df = pd.DataFrame(adata.X, index=adata.obs_names, columns=adata.var_names)

# Apply ComBat Regress out
sc.pp.regress_out(adata, keys=['batch'])

# Step 5: Convert back to DataFrame
regressed_expr_df = pd.DataFrame(adata.X, index=adata.obs_names, columns=adata.var_names)
print(combat_expr_df.shape)
print(regressed_expr_df.shape)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.manifold import TSNE

# 1. Match metadata to expression data
def match_meta(expr, meta):
    return meta.loc[expr.index]

combat_meta = match_meta(combat_expr_df, filtered_meta)
qn_meta = match_meta(qn_expr_df, filtered_meta)
reg_meta = match_meta(regressed_expr_df, filtered_meta)

# 2. Run t-SNE
def run_tsne(X, random_state=42):
    tsne = TSNE(
        n_components=2,
        random_state=random_state,
        perplexity=30,
        max_iter=1000  
    )
    return tsne.fit_transform(X)
combat_meta[['TSNE1', 'TSNE2']] = run_tsne(combat_expr_df)
qn_meta[['TSNE1', 'TSNE2']] = run_tsne(qn_expr_df)
reg_meta[['TSNE1', 'TSNE2']] = run_tsne(regressed_expr_df)

# 3. Define color palettes
palette_outcome = sns.color_palette("Set1", n_colors=2)      # responder2
palette_studyid = sns.color_palette("tab20", n_colors=20)    # study_ID

# 4. Plotting with save option
def plot_tsne_side_by_side(meta, method_name, save_path=None):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 10))

    # Plot 1: By responder2
    scatter1 = sns.scatterplot(
        data=meta,
        x='TSNE1', y='TSNE2',
        hue='responder2',
        palette=palette_outcome,
        s=50, alpha=0.7,
        ax=axes[0]
    )
    axes[0].set_title(f"{method_name}", fontsize=25)
    axes[0].set_xlabel("t-SNE 1", fontsize=20)
    axes[0].set_ylabel("t-SNE 2", fontsize=20)
    axes[0].tick_params(labelsize=16)

    # Plot 2: By study_ID
    scatter2 = sns.scatterplot(
        data=meta,
        x='TSNE1', y='TSNE2',
        hue='study_ID',
        palette=palette_studyid,
        s=60, alpha=0.7,
        ax=axes[1]
    )
    axes[1].set_title(f"{method_name}", fontsize=30)
    axes[1].set_xlabel("t-SNE 1", fontsize=30)
    axes[1].set_ylabel("t-SNE 2", fontsize=30)
    axes[1].tick_params(labelsize=25)

    # Remove individual legends
    axes[0].legend_.remove()
    axes[1].legend_.remove()

    # Add shared legends
    handles1, labels1 = scatter1.get_legend_handles_labels()
    handles2, labels2 = scatter2.get_legend_handles_labels()

    fig.legend(handles1, labels1, title='Responder', title_fontsize=14, fontsize=12,
               loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1.01, 1))
    fig.legend(handles2, labels2, title='Study ID', title_fontsize=14, fontsize=12,
               loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1.01, 0.5))

    plt.tight_layout()

    if save_path:
        plt.savefig(save_path, bbox_inches='tight', dpi=300)
        print(f"✅ Figure saved to {save_path}")

    plt.show()

# 5. Generate and save plots
plot_tsne_side_by_side(qn_meta, "Quantile Normalization", save_path="tsne_QN.png")
plot_tsne_side_by_side(reg_meta, "Regression", save_path="tsne_Regressed.png")
plot_tsne_side_by_side(combat_meta, "ComBat", save_path="tsne_ComBat.png")

Section 3: Model Fitting¶

Sequence Construction and Padding: To model temporal gene expression dynamics, we transformed each subject’s longitudinal data into a sequence format by concatenating gene expression vectors with their corresponding timepoints. This was done separately for each normalization method (Quantile Normalization, ComBat, and Regression-adjusted data). The sequences were padded with zeros to match the length of the longest sequence across all subjects, ensuring compatibility with deep learning models that require fixed-length inputs. Each padded dataset was accompanied by binary response labels indicating high or low antibody responders.

In [7]:
import numpy as np
from tqdm import tqdm
import os
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.sequence import pad_sequences

# Function to generate sequence data
def generate_sequence_data(expr_df, combined_meta, subject_label):
    X_seq = []
    y_seq = []
    max_seq_len = 0

    for subject_id, df_sub in tqdm(combined_meta.groupby('combined_ID'), desc="Building sequences"):
        sample_ids = df_sub.sort_values('timepoint_numeric').index  # sorted timepoints

        try:
            timepoints = df_sub.loc[sample_ids, 'timepoint_numeric'].values[:, np.newaxis]  # (T, 1)
            expr = expr_df.loc[sample_ids].values  # (T, G)

            # Combine expression and time
            features = np.concatenate([expr, timepoints], axis=1)  # (T, G+1)
            X_seq.append(features)
            y_seq.append(subject_label.loc[subject_id])
            max_seq_len = max(max_seq_len, features.shape[0])
        except KeyError:
            continue

    return X_seq, y_seq, max_seq_len

# Prepare labels
subject_label = filtered_meta.drop_duplicates('combined_ID').set_index('combined_ID')['responder2']
subject_label = subject_label.map({'High-responder': 1, 'Low-responder': 0})

# Generate sequences for each normalization method
X_seq_qn, y_seq_qn, max_len_qn = generate_sequence_data(qn_expr_df, filtered_meta, subject_label)
X_seq_cb, y_seq_cb, max_len_cb = generate_sequence_data(combat_expr_df, filtered_meta, subject_label)
X_seq_reg, y_seq_reg, max_len_reg = generate_sequence_data(regressed_expr_df, filtered_meta, subject_label)

# Determine global maximum sequence length
max_seq_len_all = max(max_len_qn, max_len_cb, max_len_reg)

# Pad sequences using GPU-enabled TensorFlow
X_padded_qn = pad_sequences(X_seq_qn, maxlen=max_seq_len_all, padding='post', dtype='float32')
X_padded_cb = pad_sequences(X_seq_cb, maxlen=max_seq_len_all, padding='post', dtype='float32')
X_padded_reg = pad_sequences(X_seq_reg, maxlen=max_seq_len_all, padding='post', dtype='float32')

# Convert labels to arrays
y_array_qn = np.array(y_seq_qn)
y_array_cb = np.array(y_seq_cb)
y_array_reg = np.array(y_seq_reg)

# Output shapes
print(f"QN padded shape:        {X_padded_qn.shape}, Labels: {y_array_qn.shape}")
print(f"ComBat padded shape:    {X_padded_cb.shape}, Labels: {y_array_cb.shape}")
print(f"Regressed padded shape: {X_padded_reg.shape}, Labels: {y_array_reg.shape}")

PCA + Logistic Regression Model:
To establish a baseline for longitudinal prediction, we implemented a logistic regression model using principal components derived from gene expression data. Specifically, we performed PCA on the normalized gene expression matrix and selected the top 10 principal components as input features, which together explained over 80% of the total variance—ensuring the major biological signal was retained while reducing dimensionality and multicollinearity. The numeric timepoint of each sample was included as an additional covariate.

In [8]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import gc
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, f1_score, roc_auc_score
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
import statsmodels.api as sm
import patsy

def run_logistic_pipeline(expr_df, meta_df, method_name, seed_list = [2368, 5272, 9289, 1251, 8825, 355]):
    results = []

    # 1. Ensure matching index
    assert all(expr_df.index == meta_df.index), "Mismatch in sample order"

    # 2. Binary response
    y_array = meta_df["responder2"].map({'High-responder': 1, 'Low-responder': 0}).values
    y_array = pd.to_numeric(y_array, errors="coerce")

    # 3. PCA transformation
    pca = PCA(n_components=100)
    X_pca = pca.fit_transform(expr_df.values)

    # 4. Time feature scaling
    time_feature = meta_df["timepoint_numeric"].astype(float).values.reshape(-1, 1)
    time_feature = StandardScaler().fit_transform(time_feature)

    # 5. Combine features
    X_final = np.concatenate([X_pca, time_feature], axis=1)
    columns = [f"PC{i+1}" for i in range(X_pca.shape[1])] + ["Time"]
    full_df = pd.DataFrame(X_final, columns=columns)
    full_df["y"] = y_array

    # 6. Stratified Cross-validation
    for seed in seed_list:
        print(f"\n=== {method_name} | Seed {seed} ===")
        skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=seed)

        for fold, (train_idx, test_idx) in enumerate(skf.split(X_final, y_array)):
            print(f"  Fold {fold+1}")
            train_df = full_df.iloc[train_idx].copy()
            test_df = full_df.iloc[test_idx].copy()

            try:
                # Design matrices for logistic regression
                formula = "y ~ " + " + ".join(columns)
                y_train, X_train = patsy.dmatrices(formula, data=train_df, return_type='dataframe')
                y_train = y_train.values.ravel()

                # Fit logistic regression
                model = sm.Logit(y_train, X_train)
                result = model.fit(disp=False)

                # Predict on test set
                X_test = patsy.dmatrix(" + ".join(columns), data=test_df, return_type='dataframe')
                y_pred_prob = result.predict(X_test)
                y_pred = (y_pred_prob > 0.5).astype(int)

                acc = accuracy_score(test_df["y"], y_pred)
                f1 = f1_score(test_df["y"], y_pred)
                auc = roc_auc_score(test_df["y"], y_pred_prob)

                results.append({
                    "method": method_name,
                    "seed": seed,
                    "fold": fold + 1,
                    "accuracy": acc,
                    "f1": f1,
                    "auc": auc
                })


            except Exception as e:
                print(f"⚠️ {method_name} failed on seed {seed}, fold {fold+1}: {e}")
                continue

            gc.collect()

    return pd.DataFrame(results)

# === Run Logistic Regression for all normalization methods ===
results_qn  = run_logistic_pipeline(qn_expr_df, filtered_meta, "QN")
results_cb  = run_logistic_pipeline(combat_expr_df, filtered_meta, "ComBat")
results_reg = run_logistic_pipeline(regressed_expr_df, filtered_meta, "Regression")

# === Combine and save results ===
all_results = pd.concat([results_qn, results_cb, results_reg], ignore_index=True)
all_results.to_csv("logistic_regression_results.csv", index=False)

# === Print results ===
print("\n✅ Combined Logistic Regression Results:")
print(all_results.sort_values(["method", "seed", "fold"]))

RNN, LSTM, and GRU Models:
To capture temporal patterns in the longitudinal gene expression data, we implemented three deep learning sequence models: SimpleRNN, LSTM, and GRU. Each model was designed with a single recurrent layer of 64 hidden units followed by a dropout layer (rate = 0.4) to reduce overfitting and a final dense sigmoid output layer for binary classification. We used a masking layer to handle varying sequence lengths and padded all sequences to a unified maximum time length. The models were trained with the Adam optimizer (learning rate = 1e-4), binary cross-entropy loss, and a batch size of 64 for 20 epochs. To ensure robust evaluation, stratified 5-fold cross-validation was repeated across six random seeds. These hyperparameters were chosen based on common practice in biomedical time-series modeling and to maintain consistency across architectures for fair comparison across batch correction methods (Quantile Normalization, ComBat, and Regression).

import os
import tensorflow as tf
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import gc
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, f1_score, roc_auc_score
from tensorflow.keras import backend as K


# === RNN Model Builder ===
def build_rnn_model(input_dim):
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Masking(mask_value=0.0, input_shape=(None, input_dim)),
        tf.keras.layers.SimpleRNN(64, return_sequences=False),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.4),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
    ])
    model.compile(
        optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-4),
        loss='binary_crossentropy',
        metrics=['accuracy']
    )
    return model

# === Cross-Validation Runner ===
def run_rnn_cv(X, y, label, out_csv=None):
    seed_list = [2368, 5272, 9289, 1251, 8825, 355]
    all_results = []

    for seed in seed_list:
        print(f"\n=== {label} | Seed {seed} ===")
        kf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=seed)

        for fold, (train_idx, test_idx) in enumerate(kf.split(X, y)):
            print(f"  Fold {fold+1}")

            X_train, X_test = X[train_idx], X[test_idx]
            y_train, y_test = y[train_idx], y[test_idx]

            model = build_rnn_model(input_dim=X.shape[2])
            model.fit(
                X_train, y_train,
                epochs=20,
                batch_size=64,
                validation_split=0.2,
                verbose=0
            )

            y_pred_prob = model.predict(X_test, verbose=0).ravel()
            y_pred = (y_pred_prob > 0.5).astype(int)

            acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
            f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
            auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_prob)

            print(f"    Accuracy: {acc:.3f} | F1: {f1:.3f} | AUC: {auc:.3f}")

            all_results.append({
                "method": label,
                "seed": seed,
                "fold": fold + 1,
                "accuracy": acc,
                "f1": f1,
                "auc": auc
            })

            del model
            K.clear_session()
            gc.collect()

    results_df = pd.DataFrame(all_results)
    print(f"\n📄 Saving {label} results to: {out_csv if out_csv else 'not saved (out_csv=None)'}")
    print(results_df)
    if out_csv:
        results_df.to_csv(out_csv, index=False)
    return results_df

# === Run and Combine Results ===
results_qn = run_rnn_cv(X_padded_qn, y_array_qn, label="QN")
results_cb = run_rnn_cv(X_padded_cb, y_array_cb, label="ComBat")
results_reg = run_rnn_cv(X_padded_reg, y_array_reg, label="Regression")

combined_results_df = pd.concat([results_qn, results_cb, results_reg], ignore_index=True)
combined_results_df.to_csv("rnn_all_methods.csv", index=False)
print("✅ Combined RNN results saved to rnn_all_methods.csv")

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import gc
import tensorflow as tf
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, f1_score, roc_auc_score
from tensorflow.keras import backend as K

# 🔧 LSTM Model Builder
def build_lstm_model(input_dim):
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Masking(mask_value=0.0, input_shape=(None, input_dim)),
        tf.keras.layers.LSTM(64, return_sequences=False),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.4),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
    ])
    model.compile(optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-4),
                  loss='binary_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

# 🔁 Cross-Validation Runner
def run_lstm_cv(X_padded, y_array, label="QN"):
    seed_list = [2368, 5272, 9289, 1251, 8825, 355]
    all_results = []

    for seed in seed_list:
        print(f"\n=== LSTM with {label} | Seed {seed} ===")
        skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=seed)

        for fold, (train_idx, test_idx) in enumerate(skf.split(X_padded, y_array)):
            print(f"  Fold {fold+1}")

            X_train, X_test = X_padded[train_idx], X_padded[test_idx]
            y_train, y_test = y_array[train_idx], y_array[test_idx]

            model = build_lstm_model(input_dim=X_padded.shape[2])
            model.fit(
                X_train, y_train,
                epochs=20,
                batch_size=64,
                validation_split=0.2,
                verbose=0
            )

            y_pred_prob = model.predict(X_test, verbose=0).ravel()
            y_pred = (y_pred_prob > 0.5).astype(int)

            acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
            f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
            auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_prob)

            print(f"    Accuracy: {acc:.3f} | F1: {f1:.3f} | AUC: {auc:.3f}")

            all_results.append({
                "method": label,
                "seed": seed,
                "fold": fold+1,
                "accuracy": acc,
                "f1": f1,
                "auc": auc
            })

            del model
            K.clear_session()
            gc.collect()

    return pd.DataFrame(all_results)

# 🧪 Run LSTM for all normalization methods
results_qn  = run_lstm_cv(X_padded_qn, y_array_qn, label="QN")
results_cb  = run_lstm_cv(X_padded_cb, y_array_cb, label="ComBat")
results_reg = run_lstm_cv(X_padded_reg, y_array_reg, label="Regression")

# 💾 Save results
combined_results_df = pd.concat([results_qn, results_cb, results_reg], ignore_index=True)
combined_results_df.to_csv("lstm_all_methods.csv", index=False)
print("✅ LSTM results saved to lstm_all_methods.csv")

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import gc
import tensorflow as tf
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, f1_score, roc_auc_score
from tensorflow.keras import backend as K

# 🔧 GRU Model Builder
def build_gru_model(input_dim):
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Masking(mask_value=0.0, input_shape=(None, input_dim)),
        tf.keras.layers.GRU(64, return_sequences=False),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.4),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
    ])
    model.compile(optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-4), 
                  loss='binary_crossentropy', 
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

# 🔁 Cross-Validation Runner
def run_gru_cv(X_padded, y_array, label="QN"):
    seed_list = [2368, 5272, 9289, 1251, 8825, 355]
    all_results = []

    for seed in seed_list:
        print(f"\n=== GRU with {label} | Seed {seed} ===")
        skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=seed)

        for fold, (train_idx, test_idx) in enumerate(skf.split(X_padded, y_array)):
            print(f"  Fold {fold+1}")

            X_train, X_test = X_padded[train_idx], X_padded[test_idx]
            y_train, y_test = y_array[train_idx], y_array[test_idx]

            model = build_gru_model(input_dim=X_padded.shape[2])

            model.fit(
                X_train, y_train,
                epochs=20,
                batch_size=64,
                validation_split=0.2,
                verbose=0
            )

            y_pred_prob = model.predict(X_test, verbose=0).ravel()
            y_pred = (y_pred_prob > 0.5).astype(int)

            acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
            f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
            auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_prob)

            print(f"    Accuracy: {acc:.3f} | F1: {f1:.3f} | AUC: {auc:.3f}")

            all_results.append({
                "method": label,
                "seed": seed,
                "fold": fold+1,
                "accuracy": acc,
                "f1": f1,
                "auc": auc
            })

            del model
            K.clear_session()
            gc.collect()

    return pd.DataFrame(all_results)

# 🧪 Run GRU CV for each batch correction method
results_qn  = run_gru_cv(X_padded_qn, y_array_qn, label="QN")
results_cb  = run_gru_cv(X_padded_cb, y_array_cb, label="ComBat")
results_reg = run_gru_cv(X_padded_reg, y_array_reg, label="Regression")

# 💾 Save results
combined_results_df = pd.concat([results_qn, results_cb, results_reg], ignore_index=True)
combined_results_df.to_csv("gru_all_methods.csv", index=False)
print("✅ GRU results saved to gru_all_methods.csv")

Transformer Model:
To capture complex temporal patterns and feature interactions in longitudinal gene expression data, we implemented a custom Transformer architecture. The model uses a separate learnable MLP-based time embedding to integrate timepoint information alongside gene expression features. These inputs are combined and passed through a self-attention mechanism (MultiHeadAttention with 4 heads and key dimension 64), followed by global average pooling, dense layers, and dropout for regularization. The final output layer performs binary classification to predict immune response. We trained the model using the Adam optimizer with a learning rate of 1e-4, using a batch size of 64 and 20 training epochs. Stratified 5-fold cross-validation was conducted with six random seeds.

import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras import layers, models
import numpy as np
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, roc_auc_score
class TimeEmbedding(layers.Layer):
    def __init__(self, embed_dim):
        super().__init__()
        self.mlp = models.Sequential([
            layers.Dense(embed_dim, activation='relu'),
            layers.Dense(embed_dim)
        ])

    def call(self, time_input):
        return self.mlp(time_input)  # shape: (batch, time, embed_dim)

class TransformerBlock(tf.keras.layers.Layer):
    def __init__(self, embed_dim, num_heads, ff_dim, rate=0.1):
        super().__init__()
        self.att = tf.keras.layers.MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=num_heads, key_dim=embed_dim)
        self.ffn = tf.keras.Sequential([
            tf.keras.layers.Dense(ff_dim, activation='relu'),
            tf.keras.layers.Dense(embed_dim)
        ])
        self.layernorm1 = tf.keras.layers.LayerNormalization()
        self.layernorm2 = tf.keras.layers.LayerNormalization()
        self.dropout1 = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(rate)
        self.dropout2 = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(rate)

    def call(self, x, training=None):  # 👈 Add training=None
        attn_output = self.att(x, x, training=training)
        out1 = self.layernorm1(x + self.dropout1(attn_output, training=training))
        ffn_output = self.ffn(out1)
        return self.layernorm2(out1 + self.dropout2(ffn_output, training=training))
    
def build_transformer(input_dim, embed_dim=64, num_heads=4, ff_dim=128, max_len=100):
    gene_input = layers.Input(shape=(None, input_dim))  # (batch, time, gene_features)
    time_input = layers.Input(shape=(None, 1))           # (batch, time, 1)

    time_embed = TimeEmbedding(embed_dim)(time_input)
    x = layers.Dense(embed_dim)(gene_input)  # project gene features
    x = layers.Add()([x, time_embed])        # add time embedding

    x = TransformerBlock(embed_dim, num_heads, ff_dim)(x)

    x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling1D()(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)
    x = layers.Dense(64, activation='relu')(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)
    output = layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)

    model = models.Model(inputs=[gene_input, time_input], outputs=output)
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import gc
import tensorflow as tf
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, f1_score, roc_auc_score
from tensorflow.keras import backend as K

# 🔧 Transformer Model Builder
def build_transformer(input_dim):
    gene_input = tf.keras.Input(shape=(None, input_dim), name='gene_input')
    time_input = tf.keras.Input(shape=(None, 1), name='time_input')

    x = tf.keras.layers.Concatenate(axis=-1)([gene_input, time_input])
    x = tf.keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.LayerNormalization()(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=4, key_dim=64)(x, x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.GlobalAveragePooling1D()(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.4)(x)
    output = tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)

    model = tf.keras.Model(inputs=[gene_input, time_input], outputs=output)
    model.compile(optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-4),
                  loss='binary_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

# 🔁 Cross-Validation Runner
def run_transformer_cv(X_gene, X_time, y_array, label="QN"):
    seed_list = [2368, 5272, 9289, 1251, 8825, 355]
    all_results = []

    for seed in seed_list:
        print(f"\n=== Transformer with {label} | Seed {seed} ===")
        skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=seed)

        for fold, (train_idx, test_idx) in enumerate(skf.split(X_gene, y_array)):
            print(f"  Fold {fold+1}")

            X_train_gene, X_test_gene = X_gene[train_idx], X_gene[test_idx]
            X_train_time, X_test_time = X_time[train_idx], X_time[test_idx]
            y_train, y_test = y_array[train_idx], y_array[test_idx]

            model = build_transformer(input_dim=X_gene.shape[2])

            model.fit(
                [X_train_gene, X_train_time], y_train,
                epochs=20,
                batch_size=64,
                validation_split=0.2,
                verbose=0
            )

            y_pred_prob = model.predict([X_test_gene, X_test_time], verbose=0).ravel()
            y_pred = (y_pred_prob > 0.5).astype(int)

            acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
            f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
            auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_prob)

            print(f"    Accuracy: {acc:.3f} | F1: {f1:.3f} | AUC: {auc:.3f}")

            all_results.append({
                "method": label,
                "seed": seed,
                "fold": fold+1,
                "accuracy": acc,
                "f1": f1,
                "auc": auc
            })

            del model
            K.clear_session()
            gc.collect()

    return pd.DataFrame(all_results)

# 🧪 Run Transformer CV for each normalization method
G_qn = X_padded_qn.shape[2] - 1
df_qn = run_transformer_cv(X_padded_qn[:, :, :G_qn], X_padded_qn[:, :, G_qn:], y_array_qn, label="QN")

G_cb = X_padded_cb.shape[2] - 1
df_cb = run_transformer_cv(X_padded_cb[:, :, :G_cb], X_padded_cb[:, :, G_cb:], y_array_cb, label="ComBat")

G_reg = X_padded_reg.shape[2] - 1
df_reg = run_transformer_cv(X_padded_reg[:, :, :G_reg], X_padded_reg[:, :, G_reg:], y_array_reg, label="Regression")

# 💾 Save results
transformer_results_df = pd.concat([df_qn, df_cb, df_reg], ignore_index=True)
transformer_results_df.to_csv("transformer_all_methods.csv", index=False)
print("✅ Transformer results saved to transformer_all_methods.csv")

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Melt the DataFrame
plot_df = combined_df.melt(
    id_vars=['method', 'model'],
    value_vars=['f1', 'accuracy', 'auc'],
    var_name='Metric',
    value_name='Score'
)

# Set model order (must match 'model' column values exactly)
model_order = ['PCA_Logistic', 'RNN', 'LSTM', 'GRU', 'Transformer']

# Custom color palette
custom_palette = ['#87CEEB', '#009ACD', '#003F5C']

# === AUC Plot (with legend) ===
metric = 'auc'
df_metric = plot_df[plot_df['Metric'] == metric]

plt.figure(figsize=(17, 10))
sns.barplot(
    data=df_metric,
    x='model', y='Score', hue='method',
    ci=95,
    palette=custom_palette,
    order=model_order,
    errorbar='sd'
)

plt.title('AUC', fontsize=30)
plt.xlabel('Model', fontsize=30)
plt.ylabel('AUC Score', fontsize=30)
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right', fontsize=25)
plt.yticks(fontsize=25)
plt.ylim(0, 1)
plt.legend(
    title='Batch Method', title_fontsize=22, fontsize=20,
    loc='center left',
    bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 0.5),
    borderaxespad=0
)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("auc_plot.png", dpi=300)
plt.show()

# === F1 and Accuracy Plots (no legend) ===
metrics_to_plot = ['f1', 'accuracy']
titles = {'f1': 'F1 Score', 'accuracy': 'Accuracy'}

for metric in metrics_to_plot:
    df_metric = plot_df[plot_df['Metric'] == metric]

    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))
    sns.barplot(
        data=df_metric,
        x='model', y='Score', hue='method',
        ci=95,
        palette=custom_palette,
        order=model_order,
        errorbar='sd'
    )

    plt.title(titles[metric], fontsize=30)
    plt.xlabel('Model', fontsize=30)
    plt.ylabel(f'{titles[metric]}', fontsize=30)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right', fontsize=25)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=25)
    plt.ylim(0, 1)
    plt.legend([], [], frameon=False)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(f"{metric}_plot.png", dpi=300)
    plt.show()
